                <p>The emphasis on low-end torque is further highlighted by Ducati's claim that a substantial amount of the peak torque will be available from as low as 3,000 rpm. This is the heart of the "New Panigale V2" philosophy: a high-performance machine that is genuinely exhilarating and easier to manage in real-world riding conditions.</p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Aesthetics and Ergonomics: Sharp Design, Friendlier Ride</h3>
                <p>The visual cues of the 2025 Panigale V2 are expected to draw heavily from its Panigale V4 sibling, ensuring it retains that unmistakable Ducati superbike flair. The design will be sharper, more aggressive, and aerodynamically refined.</p>
                <p>A key highlight is the focus on <span class="font-weight-700">thermal comfort</span>. Ducati has reportedly redesigned the air-flow system with new fairing ducts and channels to better dissipate engine heat away from the rider, a major improvement over the outgoing model.</p>
                <p>In terms of ergonomics, the new Panigale V2 is anticipated to be slightly more street-friendly. The clip-ons are rumored to be mounted higher than its predecessor, providing a less aggressive, yet still sporty, riding position. This small but significant change will greatly improve rider comfort during city commutes and long rides, without compromising its capability on the racetrack.</p>
                <p>The bike is also expected to feature a new, compact, and lighter aluminum monocoque frame, contributing to a substantial weight reduction—potentially by as much as 17 kg (dry weight) compared to the previous version, bringing the total kerb weight to around 179 kg (standard model). This dramatic weight loss will be a major factor in improving agility and handling.</p>
                <h3 class="subheading">Benchmark Electronics and Rider Aids</h3>
                <p>Ducati has always been at the forefront of motorcycle electronics, and the 2025 Panigale V2 is no exception. It is expected to come equipped with a full suite of modern, six-axis Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU)-managed rider aids, similar to the Panigale V4.</p>
